record.text: People really assume I actually know who people are just because most people do; or that I know whatever has been going on in the trans community on twitter. I've literally just been in my little corner of the world trying to survive.

we're already using hive.ai for image classification, its alright, kinda pricey, and not the most accurate, but it solves the immediate issue for us for now.

I bet i could hack something better together pretty quickly, but running ML infra isnt something we are set up for yet

Need more training data. Current model thinks that a post containing just the word "pestilence" has a bad vibe.

Idk, maybe its right?
No idea about sentiment but what's the state of the art on image classification rn? Yahoo's is_nsfw is probably pretty dated by now.

if we reduce it back down to ooda loops, then decisions require updates in orientation, which in turn require updates in observation (& if u want to complete the loop in reverse, observations require updates in actions)

willing to bet that people dont make decisions bc they dont know what they want

fascinating how tech is trending away from decisions, and users (at least me, in revealed preference) actually want this

google search and pick result -> chatgpt prompt and one immediate result

pick a youtbe video -> play youtube shorts / scroll tiktok

why don't people like taking decisions?

you could argue that its a fear of consequences, but definitely isnt the case in this context

these decisions seem kinda effortful (not by much, but just enough to cause friction) ... but why are they effortful?
